RUSSIA AND NORTH KOREA AGREE ON PARTNERSHIP

Vladimir Putin announced a “new level” of ties between Russia and North Korea during his visit to the reclusive state, pledging mutual support in the event of an attack. Thousands of North Koreans welcomed Putin, who signed a strategic partnership with Kim Jong Un, replacing previous agreements from 1961, 2000, and 2001.

The new pact covers political, trade, investment, cultural, and security aspects. Putin called it a “breakthrough document” and criticized US-led joint drills as “hostile” towards North Korea. Kim described the alliance as a “watershed moment” in their relations.

The visit included elaborate ceremonies, with Putin and Kim riding through Pyongyang in an open-top limousine. This highlighted North Korea’s reliance on Russia and signaled Putin’s influence despite Western opposition following his invasion of Ukraine in 2022. Accusations of North Korean arms supplies to Russia have been denied by both nations, though evidence suggests otherwise.

Putin’s visit, his first to North Korea in 24 years, aims to deepen their alignment amid shared animosity towards the West. Kim expressed strong support for Russia’s actions in Ukraine. The growing relationship has raised concerns in Seoul and Washington about potential military cooperation and technology transfers between the two countries.

During the visit, Putin presented Kim with gifts, including an Aurus car, while Russian state media emphasized their close rapport. This meeting follows Kim’s visit to Russia last year, which marked a significant step in their relations. Observers note the trend of increasing cooperation driven by shared grievances with the West, accelerated by the war in Ukraine.

